        args='{"final_result": "\\n# Principal Valuation, Underwriting, and Allocation Decisions That Cannot Be Finalized\\n\\nThe preliminary S-1 filed May 20, 2026 omits the **offering price range** (blank as \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ to $\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ per share\\"), the **number of shares offered** (blank as \\"\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ shares of Class A common stock\\"), and the **over-allotment option shares**. These omissions create a cascading set of unresolved decisions across valuation, underwriting, and allocation that institutional investors must defer until the final prospectus is filed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## I. VALUATION DECISIONS THAT CANNOT BE FINALIZED\\n\\n### 1. Enterprise Value and Market Capitalization\\n- **Pro forma market capitalization** cannot be calculated. The filing provides **12,535,298,410 total shares outstanding** (pre-offering) as of May 1, 2026, plus a variable number of new Class A shares to be issued, but the offering price is blank. Without both variables, no enterprise value can be derived.\\n- **Implied valuation at the midpoint** of the range (used for all pro forma calculations in the filing) is unknown.\\n- The fee table shows placeholder maximums of $5.5 trillion to $7.5 trillion for 66,666,670 shares, implying per-share prices of approximately **$82,500 to $112,500**. However, these appear to be SEC registration fee calculation placeholders, not the actual price range.\\n\\n### 2. Dilution to New Investors\\n- The filing provides the **mechanism** for calculating dilution (offering price minus adjusted pro forma net tangible book value per share), but every numerical output is blank: net tangible book value per share (total and per-share), adjusted pro forma net tangible book value per share, and dilution per share.\\n- **Sensitivity analysis** is also blank: the filing states that a $1.00 change in offering price alters dilution by \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\" and a change of \\"\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ shares\\" offered alters dilution by \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\". Institutional investors cannot model entry price risk without these figures.\\n\\n### 3. Pro Forma Capitalization (Entire \\"As Adjusted\\" Column is Blank)\\nThe capitalization table as of March 31, 2026 provides actual and pro forma columns, but the **\\"Pro Forma as Adjusted\\" column is entirely blank** across every line item:\\n- Cash and cash equivalents (currently $15,852M actual)\\n- All long-term debt lines (SpaceX Bridge Loan at $20,000M, Other Financings at $9,105M, etc.)\\n- Total shareholders\' equity (currently $34,533M actual, $41,582M pro forma)\\n- Total capitalization (currently $70,693M)\\n\\nWithout this column, investors cannot assess post-IPO leverage ratios, cash position, or capital structure.\\n\\n### 4. Per-Share Economics for Comparable Valuation\\n- **Price-to-Revenue, Price-to-EBITDA, and Price-to-Book multiples** cannot be computed. FY 2025 consolidated revenue was $18,674M and Segment Adjusted EBITDA was $6,584M, but the denominator (implied market cap or enterprise value) depends on the unknown price × share count.\\n- **Per-share earnings**: Pro forma EPS for Q1 2026 is $(0.41) and FY 2025 is $(0.51) on pro forma weighted-average shares of 10,607M and 9,649M respectively. These figures are calculable, but **P/E-based valuation** cannot be anchored without the offering price (and the company is loss-making, making this moot for positive P/E, but EV/Revenue and EV/EBITDA remain unresolvable).\\n\\n### 5. Class C Conversion Price Sensitivity\\n- The Class C to Class A reclassification is nominally 1:1, but the **total number of Class A shares resulting depends on a \\"future trading price\\"** tied to the IPO. The final share count affecting all per-share metrics is therefore price-dependent.\\n\\n### 6. Investor Comparison Table\\n- The filing contains a table comparing consideration paid by **Elon Musk and existing investors** versus **new public investors**, with columns for shares acquired (number and percent), total consideration ($ and percent), and average price per share. **Every cell is blank**, preventing any assessment of how much incremental value new investors are \\"buying into\\" relative to historical capital invested by insiders.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## II. UNDERWRITING DECISIONS THAT CANNOT BE FINALIZED\\n\\n### 1. Underwriting Discount and Commission\\n- The per-share underwriting discount/commission and total fees (both with and without over-allotment exercise) are all blank. Institutional investors cannot calculate **net proceeds per share** or assess the **gross spread** as a percentage of offering price.\\n- Concessions to dealers (\\"not exceeding $\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ per share\\") are also blank.\\n\\n### 2. Net Proceeds to the Company\\n- Expected net proceeds are \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_\\" (blank) at the midpoint offering price of \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ per share.\\" With over-allotment exercise, the additional amount is also blank.\\n- **Sensitivity figures** are blank: a $1.00 price change alters proceeds by \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ million\\" and a 1M share change alters proceeds by \\"$\\\\_\\\\_\\\\_ million.\\"\\n\\n### 3. Use of Proceeds Allocation\\n- While the strategic categories are specified (AI compute infrastructure, launch infrastructure, satellite constellations, general corporate purposes, and repayment of the $20,000M SpaceX Bridge Loan), the **dollar amounts allocable to each use** cannot be determined without knowing net proceeds.\\n- The amount required to repay the SpaceX Bridge Loan may be partially or fully determinable (up to $20,000M outstanding), but the residual allocation to other uses depends on total proceeds.\\n\\n### 4. Over-Allotment (Greenshoe) Economics\\n- The number of additional shares the underwriters may purchase (at the IPO price less underwriting discount) is blank. This affects:\\n  - Total shares outstanding post-IPO (both with and without exercise are blank)\\n  - Stabilization capacity and strategy\\n  - Net cash to the company if the option is exercised\\n\\n### 5. Stabilization and Price Support Strategy\\n- Morgan Stanley is designated as the stabilization agent and may engage in covered and naked short sales. The **parameters** of the stabilization program (short position size, price bands) are implicitly determined by the offering price and size, which are unknown.\\n\\n### 6. FINRA Reimbursement Amount\\n- The company agrees to reimburse underwriters for FINRA clearance expenses up to a specified amount that is blank.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## III. ALLOCATION DECISIONS THAT CANNOT BE FINALIZED\\n\\n### 1. Directed Share Program Size\\n- The percentage of shares reserved for employees, management associates, and designated individuals (friends, family, business partners) is blank (\\"up to \\\\_\\\\_\\\\_%\\"). This directly affects:\\n  - The number of shares available for institutional allocation\\n  - Retail versus institutional demand dynamics\\n  - Post-IPO selling pressure (directed share purchases are **not subject to lock-up**)\\n\\n### 2. Retail Allocation\\n- The filing specifies that certain shares will be offered through retail platforms (Charles Schwab, Fidelity, Robinhood, SoFi, E*TRADE), but the **quantities** are not specified.\\n\\n### 3. Post-Offering Ownership and Voting Power\\n- Post-offering Class A and Class B shares outstanding are blank, as are:\\n  - Voting power percentages for Class A and Class B\\n  - Elon Musk\'s post-offering economic ownership percentage\\n  - New investor collective ownership percentage\\n- Musk\'s pre-offering voting power is **85.1%** (through 5,569,053,075 Class B shares at 10 votes each plus Class A shares), and the filing states he will retain \\"a majority of the voting power\\" post-offering, but the exact post-IPO percentages are blank.\\n\\n### 4. Lock-Up Release Quantities\\n- The 180-day lock-up for directors/officers has a staggered early-release schedule (at 70, 90, 105, 120, 135 days and after Q2/Q3 2026 earnings, plus a 30%-above-IPO-price trigger). The **number of shares eligible** for each release tranche cannot be determined without the offering price (for the performance threshold) and the total share counts.\\n- The 366-day lock-up for Elon Musk and significant investors covers \\"100% of the Founder\'s shares and an aggregate of \\\\_\\\\_\\\\_% of outstanding shares\\"—the percentage is blank.\\n\\n### 5. Book-Building and Demand Sensitivity\\n- Institutional investors cannot finalize their **indications of interest** (IOIs) without a price range, as:\\n  - Portfolio allocation sizing depends on expected per-share cost\\n  - Position sizing relative to fund NAV is price-dependent\\n  - The attractiveness of the allocation versus secondary-market alternatives (if any) or comparable public companies cannot be assessed\\n\\n### 6. Per-Share Cost Basis and Portfolio Construction\\n- Without the offering price, institutional investors cannot determine:\\n  - Their cost basis for portfolio accounting and tax lot tracking\\n  - Weighting in model portfolios or indices\\n  - Whether the allocation fits within mandate constraints (e.g., market-cap thresholds for large-cap vs. mid-cap mandates)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## SUMMARY TABLE\\n\\n| Decision Category | Specific Blanks | Downstream Impact |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Offering price range** | Low and high per share | All valuation multiples, dilution, proceeds |\\n| **Shares offered** | Base shares and over-allotment | Market cap, ownership %, voting power |\\n| **Underwriting discount** | Per share and total | Net proceeds, gross spread analysis |\\n| **Net proceeds** | With and without over-allotment | Use of proceeds allocation, bridge loan repayment |\\n| **Dilution table** | All cells | Entry-price risk assessment |\\n| **Pro forma capitalization** | Entire \\"as adjusted\\" column | Leverage ratios, cash position |\\n| **Directed share program** | Reserved percentage | Institutional allocation supply |\\n| **Post-offering own